com.versant.trans
Class VQLQuery

java.lang.Object
  com.versant.trans.VQLQuery

public class VQLQuery
extends java.lang.Object

VQLQuery -- implements queries with the Versant Query Language (VQL), which is a subset of OQLQuery specified in ODMG 2.0.

Usage:

1. Construct a VQLQuery object using a VQL predicate string.

The VQL predicate string is a query expression that conforms to the VQL specifications. Refer to VERSANT ODBMS 5.0 Concepts and Usage, Chapter 12-13 for the semantics in specifying a query expresssion. Result projection is not supported in this version, and the predicate string should be in the form of:

"select selfoid from [only] [predicate]",

where class is the name of the class over which the query operates, only is an optional argument used if the query must exclude sub-classes from being searched, and predicate is the query predicate.

2. If selecting with substitution parameters, use the bind() method to assign the substitution values. The ith variable is set by the ith call to the bind() method.

3. Call method execute() to carry out the query to return a VEnumeration. To dereference an object in the Enumeration, use method nextElement().

VEnumeration

executeWithCursor

public VEnumeration executeWithCursor(int batchSize)
Execute the VQL query and return objects that satisfy the query statement using a database cursor. A cursor query that selects objects returns a VEnumeration just as a VQL execute method does. In addition, it creates a cursor that fetches objects from the database one batch at a time, where the batch size is according to the supplied argument.

In iterating through the VEnumeration using the Object nextElement () method, the cursor is transparently advanced to fetch the next batch of objects.

By fetching batches of object at a time using a cursor rather than all the objects at once, a cursor query reduces lock contention on the fetched objects and lessens memory usage.

When you finish using a cursor you must invalidate it to release it. This can be done by invoking the invalidateCursor () method on the VEnumeration instance. All open cursors are automatically released at the end of each transaction.

Unlike the execute method without a cursor, you cannot use a VQL query string conforming to an expression other than: "SELECT FROM [ONLY] target WHERE predicate_expression" specify the number of links to traverse

To use a cursor based VQL query, you can do the following: VQLQuery query = new VQLQuery (session, "select selfoid from Person where age < 18); VEnumeration ve = q.executeWithCursor (100); // batchSize // Iterate through the enumeration // Transparently retrieves the next batch of 100 when batch boundaries // are crossed while (ve.hasMoreElements ()) { minor = (Person) ve.nextElement (); ..... }

Parameters:
batchSize - the number of elements to fetch in a cursor batch
